{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_esmond_ver01/data/sn85042373/00295863183/1914031001/0540.xml":{"full_text":"V1\n.v\n\u20224\nj'r\nI\nr'.V\nv-r\nVt\nTUESDAY, MARCH 10, 191C\nLMffiB) SALESMEN\nMEET WBXCSMY\nAnnual Convention of Bo\nvey-Shute Co. Held in\nThis City.\nPRESIDENT LIKES\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nCompany Has Been Active\nin Promoting the Better\n.Farming Movement.\nThirty-two officers and agents of the\nEovey-Shutc Lumber company are\ngathering in Grand Forks today for\nthe annual convention of the North\n!akota agents of the concern.\nThe meetings will open at the Com\nmercial club Wednesday morning, and\nwill continue through Thursday aft\nernoon. The annual banquet will be\nheld at the Hotel Dacotah at a o'clock\nWednesday evening.\nJ. A. Bovey of Minneapolis, presi\ndent of the company, will preside at\nthe meetings. A. B. Jackson of Min\nneapolis, secretary of the concern, is\nalso here.\nThe sessions scheduled for Wednes\nday morning and afternoon and\nThursday morning will be chiefly de\nvoted to the discussion of selling\nmethods and conditions, and addresses\nby salesmen of wholesale lumber sup\nplies, etc.\nHear Wire Talk.\nThursday afternoon will be devoted\nto an address by H. A. Squibba of\nMinneapolis, assistant manager of the\nfence department of thc American\nWire and Fence company Mr. Squtbbs\nwill also address the^ students of the\nschool of mines at the state university\nat 4:30 o'clock Thursday afternoon.\nHis address will be illustrated with\nmotion pictures.\nother speakers who will address the\nconvention are R. S. Boswell, manager\nof the Minneapolis Paper company,\nfind A. Kllma, manager of the King\nVentilating company of Oelwein, Iowa.\nPromote Fanning.\nOne of the most interesting ad\ndresses scheduled is that of W. G.\nConnors, better farming agent and\ncommunity expert, employed by the\ncompany.\nMr. Connors is actively engaged in\nassisting In the better farming and\ncommunity building work now being\ndone in the state, and has been active\nin the promotion of Better Farming\nsocieties in several counties. He has\nalso assisted in forming a number of\nstock breeders' associations and Com\nmercial clubs.\nNew Line of Activity.\n\"This is a new line of work for a\nlumber company to enter,\" said Mr.\nConnors this morning. \"We believe,\nhowever, that whatever benefits the\ncommunity helps our business and\n\u2022that we will get good returns from\nthe work we are doing along this\nline.\"\nBovey Well Satisfied.\n\"We are well satisfied with the pres\nent business outlook tn this state,\"\nsaid Mr. Bovey today. \"The present\nindications are that the sales of the\n\"eoththg season Will' be' even largfer\n'than usual.\n\"Collections during the last few\nmonths have also been astonishingly\ngood when the partial crop failure\nwhich ensued in several parts of the\nstate last season are considered\nThe banquet to be held at the Da\ncotah Wednesday evening is to be en\ntirely informal in character. There\nwill be no program of speeches. The\nconvention will close Thursday after\nnoon.\nThe officers of the concern who are\nto be present at the meeting are: J.\nA. Bovey, Minneapolis, president A.\nB. Jackson, Minneapolis, secretary\nF. A. Taylor, Grand Forks, superin\ntendent Iver Roaldson, New Rock\nford, superintendent.\nSalesmen to Attend.\nThe salesmen who are to be present\nare:\nW. A. Hamilton, Devils Lake: How\nard Colvin, Tokio J. H. Heimark,\nWarwick A. C. Wild. Kgeland A, C.\nStrassman, Mylo William Campbell,\nOmemee A. J. Grace, Leeds Ole\nChrlstcnson, Rugby C. H. Rudd, Ml\nnot H. G. Hansen, Williston R. L.\nInformation for aD\nLung Sufferers\nWould you Uke te know more about\n(wmedr for Lung Trouble which baa\nUr\u2014\"\nif\n\u2022rougbt about many complete recoveri\u00ab\u00abt\n|rhe makers of Eckmah's Alterative are\nreceipt of many really wonderful re\ntorts, and will be pleated to forward to\nletter* and also\nre needed in\nthis caae:\u2014\nforts, and will be pleased\nou copies of original le\nooklet on diet ana proper\nlecovering health. lover\n161#oi\npi\n1\n0\nll\n:f-\n*r J\"\nnf.:\nI'/-.\nrf'\n,#V\nI#\nP'\nli' I\niper care needed in\nlitigate this caae:-\n1619 fluMuehsiftia Ave,, Fhlia., Ps.\n'Mr Dear Bit: For two years I was\nitfflleted with hemorrhage* of the longs.\nUnd in February of 1U02 I was taken with\nsevere attack of pneumonia. When I\nream-red safflcientlr to walk about the\nhome I was left with a frightful hacking\ncough, which no medicine I had taken\neoold alleviate. It was at this time,\nMarch. 1902, that I started taking Ecfc\nBan'a Alterative. In a short time uw\nrough was'gone and I was proooenced\nW*'L\nf*Bn? speak too highly tor the\ngood it has done.\"\n(Signed) HOWARD L. KLOTZ.\nany years'_t*t to bejmoat efieactoa*.\n'or never* Throat and lung Affectlona,\n.Bronchitis. Bronchial Aithma, Stubborn\nColds and In apbnUdlnK the system.\nContains no narcotic\u00ae, potions or baMt\nfornilng drags. Aak for booklet telling\nMl recoveries, sad- write te Bekmsa\nlaboratory, Philadelphia, Pa., for eri\nUsee.' For aale by all leading draggMa\nBi\nI\n^-v\n1-\nipgJjK\ni5H\n\u2022A\u00bb?\n1\nBudde, Karlsruhe H. P. Peterson,\nBran Word S.' -T.- Hanking, Sheyenne\nK. A. Ousdahl, Oberon C. O. Jacot,\nMinnewaukan Martin Bergouat,\nFlora I. J. .Hauge. Maddock Vi A.\nBletner, Baker E. J. Smith, Fillmore\nC. M. Wilson, Silva Charles Richard\nson, Plaza J. T5. Kimball,. Makoti G.\nI* Wertzler, Ryder Clinton Colvin,\nRuso E. D. Knapton, Dogden George\nProchal, Drake.\nNK SUMS\nENTER CONTEST\nAnnual Oratorical Event at\nUniversity Will be\nGood.\nThe annual oratorical contest at the\nstate university this year promises to\nbe *ne of the best ever held at the\ninstitution. Nine contestants have\nhanded in orations and aimong this\nnumber there are several\n1\u00b0\nexcellent\nspeakers. For the first time in the\nhistory of the university, a. girl has\nentered the contest, an oration being\nhanded in by Miss Inga Lelne, while\nthc other entrants are all men. The\nlist includes Lester M. Smith, Clifford\nHanson. Axel Aronson, Charles He\nmans, William Chittlck, Edward Mc\nIlraitii, Howard Huston and Randall\nLarson.\nBoard Meets Today.\nA special meeting of, the oratorical\nboard Vs scheduled to take place at the\nuniversity at 4:30 o'clock this after\nnoon and plans for the contest will\nbe discussed at that time. It is ex\npected tiia.t a preliminary event .will\nbe hold. in. the next few days, BO as to\ncut thc number of speakers down to\nlive or six. This will, make a much\nbetter contest' in every way.\nThe preliminary contest will consist\nmerely .of judging on thought and\ncom position. The final awards will\nbe inado on'delivery, as well' as\nthougllt and composition. Judges Tor\nthe contests will be named at the\nmeeting- of the board this afternoon.\nThe contestants have been asked to\nconfer .with the board in regard to the\npreliminary affair.\nFinal Kvcnt March 29.\nThe final iiontest wiii.be held at the\nuniversity Friday evening, March 27.\nThe winner of first place will be pre\nsented with the Merrlfleld $30 prize,\nand will also represent the university\nin the state contest here next month.\nThe winner of second prize will be giv\nen the $20 Merrlfleld prize.\nThe winner of first place in the state\nevent will represent North Dakota in\nthe contest with South Dakota and\nwill be presented with a beautiful gold\nwatch, which is the annual gift of\nthe Masonic grand lodge of the state.\nThe university contest was won last\"\nyear by-Francis Tenipleton.\nMANY REAL ESTATE TRANSFERS\nI Are Recorded Burins Last Two Days\nat Office of A. 1. Lodmell,\nRegister of Deeds.\nA large number of real estate trans\nfers have been recorded during the\nlast two days by A. M. Lodmell, coun\nty register of deeds, the latest being\nthat of two' lots in Budge and Eshel\nman's addition to Grand Forks by W.\nE.. Fuller, to Haakon Johnson for\n$3,000.\n..The following .warranty deeds were\nfiled yesterday: Hans Otteson to Mrs.\nMary C. Smith, two lots in block 29 of\nLindsay's addition to the city of\nGrand Forks, consideration $1,400 G.\nIt. Holton to Hans Otteson, two lots\nin Lindsay's addition, consideration\n$1,246 A. G. Ahrendt and wife to\nJustin H. Beatty, a lot In Stone's ad\ndition to the city of Grand Forks, con\nsideration private Christens Johnson\nand husband to-W. I. Forbes, a quar\nter section of land in Mekinock, con\nsideration private Chas. W. Bain and\nwife to John Langstraat, forty acres\nin Gtlby, consideration $3,400 Annie\nBain and husband to John Langstraat,\na quarter section of land in Gllby\ntownship, consideration $13,600 Hen-:\nry T. Nerkirk and wife to A. H. Coch\nran, half section in Levant township,\nconsideration $24,000 John H. Void\nand Chas. H. Nelson to Qlaf Svendrei,\na half section of land in Elkmount\ntownship, consideration private.\nBURLESON BACKBY MARCH 25\nLetters Received Today Tell of Im\nprovement of Rector of St. Paul's\nEpiscopal Cliurcli.\nRev. John K. Burleson, rector of\nSt. Paul's Episcopal church in this\ncity^ who has been ill at Kilbourn,\nWis., during the last two months, will\nreturn to Grand Forks March 25, ac\ncording to letters received from him\ntoday by friends in this city.\nMr. Burleson states that although\nhe is still rather weak as thc result\nof thc operation which he underwent,\nhe is now able to leave the house\nand walks about half a mile each day.\nHe is steadily gaining strength,\nand. is very anxious to return to\nGrand Forks. He expects to be able\nto travel in the course of the next\ntwo weeks or so, and to reach Grand\nForks by, March 25.\nLooking for a Tailor?\n.Are you looking tor somebody who\nwill build your new spring outflt and\ndo it right? Let us tempt you to take\nten of your busy .minutes today and\ncome' and look at.our spring showing.\n.Wj? are, equipped to give -good eerv Ice\nat reasonable pribes. Our garments\nare made to (It you\u2014and guaranteed\nto give satisfaction. Will you come\nand look at the fabrics? Paulson\nBros., tailors, 115 South Third street.\n'-^Adv\nMcGRATH'S SPECIAL\nPEROXIDE BATH SOAP\n/rOur new special Peroxide bath soap,\nr, keeps the complexion fair and good,\nIts fragrance and. purity is linexcell\ned. Try a.cake at\n10c, 3 for 25c\nMany other lines ranging in price\nfrom 10c to $1,00.\nMcGrath Pharmacy\nW- \u2022-.'a\n\"y- ft *^'7\n3\n1\n,4 *t\n-t C- ~f\nF08NER MOTS\nAffi ffiASD FROM\nAnnual Roll Call of Odd Fel\nlow and Rebekah Lodg\nes Responded to.\nOVER 900 ATTEND\nBIG CELEBRATION\nSocial Features Carried. Out ichants\nby the Local Lodges\nLast Evening.\nOver 300 members ef the local\nlodges of Odd Fellows and Rebckahs,\nand their friends, gathered at'the Odd\nFellows' hall Monday night for the\nannual roll call of the two orders.\nAll members of the' societies who\nwere present answered to their names\nin person, while letters were read from\na number of former members who\nhave now left the city.\nAmong the former members of the\nlodge who were heard from lt| this\nway were Leonard West, Cashmere.\nWash., Dr. W. F. Harlan, Arbuckie,\nCal., W. H. Hoffstad, Aitken, Minn.,\nT. O. McElroy, Long Beach, Cal- C. A.\nSpoklie, Sanborn, and. J. G. Crites of\nLisbon.\nThe roll 'call was interspersed. with\nmusical numbers by the Banner lodge\ndouble quartette,. consisting of X'els\nNordiund, George Buckingham Ed.\nBuckingham, Leslie Pratt, Andrew\nArmstrong, Adam Common, S S.' Gas\nwell iind Jacob Welch.\nEugene Secord gave the chief ad\ndress of the evening, telling of the\nwork being done by the order.\nSupper wan served by the members\nof the Rebekahs.. in dairy- lunch style,\nand 'the evening was concluded with\ndancing.'\nNOKVAL BAPTf\nTOm HERE\nWorld's Champion Skater\nWill Give Exhibition\nOther Events.\nJVorval Baptte, world's professional\nchampipn Ice skater, arrived in the\ncity this morning and today complet\ned arrangements for giving an ex\nhibition at the local skating ri'nk'Fri\nday night, March 13. Manager J. C.\nSheppard hag announced a double\ncard for that night. Following Is the\nprogram:\nN'orval Baptie in figure skating.\nMile relay race for boys, ten years\nI and under.\nCouple race, gentleman and lady,\nopen, to all.\nRace, Baptie backward, \\ns. local'\nman skating forward.\nGrade school, relay race, each team\nmade up of boys 14 years old and\nunder.\nExhibition of skating on stilts bv\nBaptie.\nGeneral skating for public for ten\nminutes.\nFox chase and jumping exhibition\nby Baptie.\nFollowing the jumping exhibition\nthere will be public skating for the\nremainder of the evening.\nTWO MORE GIRLS ATTACKED\n\"Javk the Hugger\" Said to Be Opcrat\ning In South End District\u2014No\nCine to His Identity.\nAnother attempted outrage against\ngirls of the city which may be the act\nof the same \"Jack the Hugger\" who\nhas lately been active on the north\nside, was reported Monday -night,\nwhen it was learned that two giris\nhad been attacked on Belmont ave\nnue, between Third and Fourth ave\nnues, last Saturday evening.\nThe affair occurred at about -'8:30\no'clock in the evening, according to\nthe girls' story. A tall man, dressed\nIn gray clothes, and apparently about\n45 years of age, stepped out of an al\nley as they were passing and attempt\ned to embrace one of them.\nBoth girls screamed and the .\"hug\nger\" aparently became frightened,\nand took to his heels. A search in\netituted a few moments later by some\nof the residents of the neighborhood\nwho had been attracted by the cries\nof the girls failed to yield any trace\nI of the attacker.\n1ALK GOOD BOADS CAMPAIGN\nPlans for Work During the Cuming\nSeason Will Be Disru.-rsei! at\nMeeting Today.\nPlans for good roads work in Grand\nForks county will be informally dis\ncussed'at a meeting of the Commer\nc!al club, good roade committee this\nafternoon. W. H. Kelaey, chairman\nof the committee, called the meeting\nfor 4 o'clock.\nThere Is every indication that good\nroads-work will be one of the features\nof the Commercial club activities dur\ning tse summer, and the committee is\nmeeting this afternoon to.get an early\nstart. There ia much to be done in\nthe county and in connection with the\nWonderland trail, and -tentative plans\nprobably will' be outlined this after\nnoon,\nThe committee consists of W. H.\nKeleey, F. B. Feethaim, J. R. Poupore,\nThomaa Moore and C. J. Murphy.\nNE.V TEIMCO. MANAGER\nG. F. Beatty Succeeds V. M. Way with\nNorthwestern Company-\u2014Lattcr\nNow with Wholesale Firm.\nGeorge F. Beatty, formerly of Fer\ngus'Falls, Minn., has been appointed\nmanager of the local exchange of the\nNorthwestern Telephone company' in\nplace of V. M. Way, who has resigned.\nMr. Beatty Is now in charge of the\nexchange. Before coming to thlq city,\nhe wa\u00ab. manager for the company at\nFergus Falls, Minn., and has had sev\neral, years of experience in telephone\nwork.\nExcept .for the retirement of Mr.\nWay, there are no other changes in\nthe stalf of the. loeal office. The for\nmer manager haa accepted a position\nas traveling salesman with the whttle\naale house of. Parte, Orant Cohri-\n'\"v still\nIA our old plfcQ# undar nattitfll'k\n\u00abi\u00bb kimm to gtvia\ntho aama oxeoUant aiailoa ta\"\nttjjgt\nmilk aonghiB Dairy\nTHE EVENING TIMES, GRAND FORKS, N D.\nllltlt\n\u2022Vc-Vd?:-.\nJ&.\nStyle Week in Grand Forks is\nMarch 17 to 21 Times-Herald\nWill Issue Special Edition\nGrand Forks merchants are making\npreparations for their 'style week.'*\nMarch 17 to 21 are the dates set, and,\njudging from present indications, it\nwill be the most elaborate and suc\ncessful \"style week\" held in the city.\nThe dealers will display all the lat\nest in ladles' and fronts* wearing ap\nparel. The Times-Herald is prepar\ning a special fashion edition, which\n[will be issued Sunday morning and\n'Which will contain all the preliminary\nannouncement^'of local merchants.\n171, TZ The ''style weel is being held for\nit of tho buyers and nier-\nof thc\nania|i''i-\nplaces of the\nCLUBS WORK ON\nProgressive Activities of the\nCommercial Organiza\ntions Show Tendencies\nProgressive Commercial clubs of\nNorth Dakota are this year enlisting\nin many lines of endeavor, the Held\nof operation 'being greater than eYer\nbefore.-?nritl\u00bb..tJio state -Federation of\nCommercial clubs meeting, in Grand\nForks-March .'16 ami 17, renewed In\nterest has beiMfe' created in club work\nin several cities, tt is believed the\nstate meet Witt be better attended\nthis year *lifiri iti sevfipftf seasons.\nRugby's clujji 1m\u00ab been ..re-organiz\ned after lying .imniant for several\nyears. A gymnasium will he eondnot'ed\nas one of tlip chili's main features.\nUnder the reorganization, Rhys Jones\nis president, _A..\u00b0. Cliristenson is vice\npresident. J. O. l.yiigstad is secretary,\nand-.-E. J. Elstad is treasurer.\nThe Granville ,-lub has taken steps\nto associate with the general imml-\n\"I have' discarded coffee altogether in my\nfamily, and instead use Postum which we\nfind n:Lkes a rich, delicious drink, without\nany of the deleterious effects attendant on\ntlic continuous use of coffee.\"\n\"Our family'have- been users of i'ostum for\n8 Ions time. Wc were very liberal coffee\ndrinkers, bul were conscious that coffee was\nharming us\u2014our nervous system, digestion\nanil heart action\u2014so we quit the coffee and\nbegan using Poatum. Now we relish it far\nmore than we did coffee, and arc all re\nlieved of the old coffee troubles. .Vs a phy\nsician 1 have induced several families lo quit\ncoffee and use I'ostum.\"\n'Tostum\u2014when it is desirable to leave\noff coffee on account of over-stimulation or\ngastric disturbances.\"\n\"Postunv has been used in my family near\nly every since it was placed on the market,\nand 1 recommend it to my patients. It is a\nnourishing drink. A great many families are\ngiving tlfeir. children Postum in place of\ncoffee with beat of results.\"\nPostum comes in two forms:\nC'.\nSjS&JK j.\ncity, as well as for local residents.\nThe Grand Forks dealers are making\nspecial arrangements for caring for\nthe out-of-town visitors.\n'Every dealer in the city has finished\nhis spring buying, and the latent ma\nterials, purchased in New York and\nother large retail centers, have reach\ned the city and will be shown for the\nfirst time next week. Dealers here\nare keeping apace with the merchants\nof the twin cities, and local residents\nnext .week will be able to see the latest\nin foreign and Aewirican wearing ap\nparel as early as they are shown in\nMinneapolis and St. I'aul.\ngration movement 'that has been\nadopted by western North Dakota\ncities.\nMilton Wants Creamery.\nMilton's flub is promoting a plan\nfor thc re-establishment of the cream\nery in that city. I!. Proin is the new\npresident of the club.\n''Sm.K'i--\n1\"\n\"EXTRA MAUE ADDITION\nIS PUBLISHED AT HOME\nOf THEODORE AHLROTH\nAn \"extra male addition\" to the\nfamily of \"Ted\" .Vlilrotli, foreman\nof the ICvonlng Times composing\nroom, arrived at Mr. Alilrotli's\nlionic on Cottonwood street at\n12 o'clock tills morning.\nAlthough It is only a fiockct ad\ndition of Mr. Alilrotli at present,\nTed says that it already weighs\neight pounds, and that the circu\nlation seems to he steadily in\ncreasing.\nTherefore Ted Is passing out\nthe \"two fers.\"\nIVtli Mrs. AId rut li mid (he new\narrival are doing well anil Tcil is\nwearing a broad grin.\nThe Chicago, Burlington and Quin\ncy railroad has grained its trainmen\nwage increases amounting to $1000,\n000 a veor.\n1\nOverwhelming Verdict\nA few month? ago, a man in no way connected with thc making of Postum or the marketing of coffee*\nwrole to quite a number of physicians all over the country asking their unbiased testimony in the case of\nPostum vs. Coffee.\nThe following excerpts from their letter? constitute an overwhelming verdict.\nIn Favor of Postum\n\"X have used Postum in my family for\nyears with the most satisfactory result,\u2014so\nmuch so that we have practically abolished\ncoffee, and with it the coffee headaches,\nnervousness, and lying awake thc best part\nof the night.\"\n\"1 drink Postum every morning, and rec\nommend it lo tny friends who have nerves'\nand indigestion.\"\n\"No more coffee for me. 1 am using In\nstant Postum and advice my patients to do\nlikewise. 1. prefer it to thc best coffee, and\nhave no more sour stumacli attacks as .1\nused to.\"\n\"For years 1 have been using Postum in\nthe family and advocating it for my patients.\n1 consider it to be exactly what its manu\nfacturers claim for it. Postum is excellent\nin piace of coffee where the latter is contra\nindicated. The food value of Postum plays\nan important part when compared with cof\nfee.\"\n\"Have had many cases that could not\ndrink coffee oil account of its reflex action\non the heart. Postum always supplies the\nplace of coffee without the bad effects.\"\nIn the-light of such testimony it would seem the part of wisdom to stop coffec and use Postum.\nPostum is a genuine, food-drink, made of whole wheat and a small per cent of molasses. Contains the\nnutritious values of the grain, but is pure and absolutely free from the coffee drug, caffeine, or any other\nharmful'substance.\nRegular Postum\u2014must be well boiled to bring out its fine flavor. 15c and 25c packages.\nInstant Postum\u2014a soluble form. A teaspoonful stirred in a cup of hot water\u2014with sugar and cream\nadded\u2014makes a delightful beverage instantly. 30c and 50c tins. The cost per cup of both kinds is the same.\n\n:-v\nThere^s a Reason\" for POSTUM\n0 7\nSPEAKER FRAME\nIS (DEPENDENT\nCandidate For Lieutenant\nGovernor Without\nAffiliations.\nSpeaker of the House J. H. Fraine\nis a candidate for the republican nom\nination for lieutenant governor, and\nIn a statement made while in the city\nlast evening, he declared his candi\ndacy is independent, of that of all\nother candidates in the field.\nMr. Fraine asserted his desire to\nabide by the spirit of the primary\nelection law of the state in making\nthe race for the nomination independ\nently.\nThe entrance of Mr. Fraine to the\nlieutenancy governorship race creates\na three-cornercii light, A. T. Kraabel,\nthe present lieutenant governor, and\nII. J. Hessessen, being previous en\ntrant.\"\nWhile lie has had the matter under\nconsideration for some time. Mr.\nFraine says his decision lias been de\nlayed because of his desire to get into\ntouch with conditions generally\nthroughout the state.\nCol.. Fraine is one of the best known\nmen in the state. Jlc has been a mem\nber of the state legislature three ses\nsions. being speaker of the house in\nthe l!13 session. He has been a resi\ndent of Walsh county thirty years.\nThe new candidate also is the com\nmanding officer\nof\n1 fji ,\u00a3*t\n1\nthe First regiment\nof the North Dakota militia. He is a\nveteran of tlie Spanish-American war.\nseeing service in the Philippine isl\nands as major of the\nSecond\nXorth Dakota regiment.\nbatallion,\nPlain Truth that's Worth Money.\n1'fling Foley's Honey and Tar tor a\n\u2022ugh or cold may save you both sick\nnews jinil money. F. F. Monalian. Mc\nnomine. \\Yi says: \"I am exposed\nt\u00bb all kinds of weather and I And\nFoley's Honey and Tar Compound al\nways ilxe\u00ab me up in good shape when\n1 catch cold or have a bad cough. I'\nrecommend it gladly.\" Refuse sub\nI utilities\u2014MctSrath's Pharmacy.\u2014Adv.\nM'\nPAGE THREE.\nMHSIREL SHOW\nPROCRAM BOUT\nBoys of Y.MC.A. Will Give\nInteresting Performance\nFriday and Saturday.\nThe complete program for the T.\nM. c\\ A. minstrel show, which will be\ngiven Friday and Saturday nights, was\na.niiouticel today. J. B. Crary, who\nhiis had charge of the preparations,\nu3 arranged an exceptionally inter\nesting program. Mr. Crary will act as\ninterlocutor. The program tor the\nopening pan. ia:\nOpening overture \"Echoes ef tbe\nPast\"\u2014Chorus.\nSolo, \"Roamin' in the Glounia'\nMorrill Cook.\nSolo, \"While the Rivers of I\u00above\nFlow On\"\u2014Krnest Coon.\nSolo. \"Sing Me the Rosary**\u2014-Orville\nMcllaflie.\nQuartet, (selected)\u2014.Morrill Cook.\n\u2022John Moore. Howard DeLong and\nErnest Coon.\nSolo. \"Peg O' My Heart'-\u2014Howard\nDcLong.\nSolo, \"Love-light Bay\"\u2014Ernest\nCoon.\nSolo, \"Pullman Porters' P\u00abnd%M\u2014\nJohn Moore.\nDuring the inwrtiiiasion, twe epeelal\nnumbers will he given. Howard Hus\nton, the Swe.de comedian, will five a\nnumber of impersonations, and R. W.\nAyres will give a blackface mono\nlogue.\nThe show will be closed with\noleo performance, \"A First CIMB HO\ntel.\" Hhe cast for this is:\nlandlord\u2014Harold Aylesworth.\nBulger, a- drummer\u2014Rmy Carter.\nLettaitt, a literary man\u2014Kenavth\nWells.\nSchnell. a. Du\ntollman\u2014He\nKneupfer.\nExcursion Majr 5.\nTiie I\n..use Land and Development\ncompany of St. Paul will open a newl\ntract of land. 14.000 acres in tbel\nHoughton Lake district, Sask. Canada.|\nLaud selling at $22 per acre, on\nterms. Agents wanted. Luse Landl\nand Development company. St. PwuLI\nBarnie Willets, district manager.\u2014J\nAil v.\n\"I have used Postum for the twt eight\nyeurs in place of coffee. Before that I was\ntroubled with frequent bilious headaches due\nto excessive use of coffee, and was then ad\nvised to u?c Postum. Since that time I have\nnot had a single attack, which effect I attri\nbute to Postum. I frequently recommend it\nto others who experience equally gratifying\nresults.\"\n\"Hardly a week goes by that I do not ad\nvi so pa it a it a a id\nstomach and nervous heart to stop at onco\nthe use of all coffee and take up the nae of\nPostum, anrl always with good results.\"\n\"L am satisfied that coffee is responaible\nin a great degree for the premature break\ndown of our active men and women, Thejr\nsuffer from caffeine poisoning. Of the truth\nof this there is not the shadow of a doubt.\nOur common sense tells us that the daily\nswallowing of caffeine\u2014over-stimulating the\nheart and brain\u2014will be followed by nervous\ndepression, and finally by more or less dis\nastrous results. I believe if people in gen\neral would use Postum as a beverage in place\nof coffee and tea their mental and physical\ncondition would be much improved.\"\n4\n-.^.V\n\u2014sold by groocn\n3 1 a\nels","height":"27611","width":"19605"}}
